Based on the foregoing observations, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as the Head of the Procuring Entity (HoPE), direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), its Secretariat and Technical Working Group (TWG) to:

consolidate the PPMPs of various implementing units and henceforth prepare the APP; 


conduct a mandatory review of the terms, conditions, cost estimates and procurement project, and on the basis thereof decide on the necessary adjustments in the technical, legal, financial eligibility requirements, if not, ensure compliance with those required under Section 23 of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;

promote and ensure transparency, competitiveness, accountability, equity, efficiency and economy in the procurement process; and


properly evaluate the mode of procurement to be used and strictly adhere with the provision set forth by the procurement law.


We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the implementing units to conduct market research and properly plan and formulate their respective PPMPs so that procurement could be done efficiently and effectively and specify the mode of implementation of infrastructure projects whether by administration or through a straight contract.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor instruct the BAC to:
incorporate in the bidding documents all relevant documents that could help validate properly the legality as well as technical and financial capacity of the prospective bidders;
invite observers in accordance with the provision of Section 13;
conduct an extensive post-qualification process; and
ensure compliance with the requirements and procedures prescribed under the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to prevent the same lapses in future procurements.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the:

concerned officials and employees strictly use the Trust Fund for its intended purpose;

BAC comply with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and issuances of the GPPB particularly on submission of required documents as well as on the posting requirements;

Municipal Mayor sends a copy of the certification to the oversight bodies mentioned in LBC No. 125 on the posting of the Report on Fund Utilization and Status of PPA Implementation; and

Municipal Accountant (i) properly record donations received by the Municipality in accordance with COA Circular No. 2014-002; (ii) ensure that supporting documents are accurate and complete before making payments; and (iii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the procurement, issuance and inventory of goods and property, plant and equipment procured by the Municipality including those received through donations either in cash or in-kind.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the GAD Focal Point System to:

ensure that 5% of the total budgets be allocated to gender-responsive PPAs;

administer the HGDG to determine the gender responsiveness of PPAS charged against the GAD budget;

submit the DILG-endorsed GAD Plan and Budget and submit the GAD Accomplishment Report; and


ensure full implementation of GAD related PPAs.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant see to it that supporting documents are complete before processing the payments.  Likewise, submit to the Audit Team the lacking supporting documents to avoid suspension in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to allocate no less than five percent (5%) of the total budget appropriations for priority programs and projects or activities that address gender issues or women’s concerns;

Establish GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) in accordance with the provisions of PCW/DILG/DBM/NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01;

Direct the assigned GAD Focal Person to submit the Annual GAD Plan to the DILG Regional Office, as appropriate, for review and approval. Likewise submit the reviewed Annual GAD Plan and Annual GAD Accomplishment Report to the Audit Team as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014.

